  <h1>ATM10: getting started with modded Minecraft</h1>
  <p class="lead">All the Mods 10 adds hundreds of mods on top of Minecraft, so the first hour can feel
  overwhelming. It is not as complicated as it looks. Here is how to get comfortable, avoid the common
  beginner frustrations, and be a good neighbour on a small shared server.</p>

  <h2>New to heavily modded Minecraft?</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <ul>
      <li><span class="em">Let it load, and give it memory.</span> The first launch is slow while all
      the mods load; that is normal, so wait it out rather than force-quitting. If the game stutters or
      crashes, raise the allocated memory in CurseForge (about 8 GB on a 16 GB computer). Too little
      memory is the number one cause of trouble.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Learn JEI first.</span> The searchable list of items down the right side of
      your inventory is <span class="em">Just Enough Items</span>. Hover an item and press
      <code>R</code> to see how to craft it, or <code>U</code> to see what it is used for. With
      thousands of new items, JEI is the tool you will use most; you rarely need a wiki.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Follow the quest book.</span> ATM10 ships an in-game guide (FTB Quests). Open
      it and work through the opening chapters: it is the intended tutorial, points you at good starter
      mods, and hands out free rewards along the way.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Go deep, not wide.</span> You cannot learn every mod at once, and trying to
      is where people burn out. Get the basics sorted (food, a shelter, a few tools), then pick
      <span class="em">one</span> mod that looks fun and follow it a good way before branching out.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Set up fast travel early.</span> Modded worlds get big and you will wander
      far. Waystones and similar blocks let you teleport back home, so you do not lose your base.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Grab what a recipe needs.</span> There is a tempting amount of loot. Take
      what the next craft calls for; you will automate the bulk gathering later, so you do not need to
      hoard everything by hand now.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>All the Mods 10 specifics</h2>
  <div class="card">
    <ul>
      <li><span class="em">There is no fixed story.</span> ATM packs are "kitchen sink": a bit of
      everything, and you choose your own path. The classic long-term goal is crafting the
      <span class="em">ATM Star</span>, a very expensive endgame item that needs a taste of nearly every
      mod. Use the quest book as your roadmap toward it, but play however you enjoy.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Get a power source going.</span> Most early progression leads into a tech
      mod for power (Mekanism, Powah, and similar are popular). The quest chapters walk you into one; you
      do not have to decide up front.</li>
      <li><span class="em">If it runs rough, turn things down.</span> Lower your render and simulation
      distance to around 8 to 12 chunks and cap your frame rate. Modded Minecraft leans on your CPU, and
      a smaller view distance helps far more than most other settings.</li>
      <li><span class="em">Only update when the server does.</span> Keep the pack on version
      {{.PackVersion}} until the server announces a change, the same as the connect guide says. Updating
      early will stop you connecting.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2>Chunk loading: why your farms stop when you log off</h2>
  <p>Minecraft only runs the part of the world close to a player. When you walk far away or log off, those
  areas <span class="em">freeze</span>: your farms, machines, and mob spawners all pause until someone is
  nearby again. That surprises a lot of new players who come back to find nothing has grown.</p>
  <p>A <span class="em">chunk loader</span> keeps the chunks you choose running even when no one is there,
  so automated farms and processing keep working while you are away. ATM10 includes
  <span class="em">FTB Chunks</span> for this: open its map, claim the area around your base, and mark the
  chunks that hold your farms as force-loaded. You get a limited number of force-loaded chunks, so spend
  them on what actually needs to keep ticking.</p>

  <div class="video">
    <div class="vtext">
      <h3>Watch: how chunk loading works</h3>
      <p>A short walkthrough of what chunk loading is and how to keep your farms and machines running
      when you are offline.</p>
    </div>
    <a class="btn" href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AHpYBhbPk80" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Watch on YouTube</a>
  </div>

  <div class="card">
    <p><span class="em">Be considerate with it.</span> Every force-loaded chunk is work the server keeps
    doing around the clock, even when you are asleep. On a small server like this one, over-loading chunks
    (claiming and force-loading big areas you do not need) is the most common cause of lag for everyone.
    Load your base and your working farms; leave the rest to load normally when you are there.</p>
  </div>

